# Day 5 - Negative Testing in Postman

## Overview

Negative testing is used to verify how an API behaves when receiving invalid, unexpected, or incorrect input.
The objective is not to prove that the API works, but to discover whether it fails in a controlled and consistent way.
A stable API should not only succeed on valid requests, but also respond predictably on invalid ones.

---

## Why Negative Testing Matters

Positive testing answers:

> Does the endpoint work under normal conditions?

Negative testing answers:

> Does the endpoint fail correctly when conditions are wrong?

This is critical because many defects appear only when inputs deviate from expected usage.

A good QA mindset assumes:

> valid cases are not enough.

---

## Test Scenario 1 - Missing ID

A common negative case for resource-based endpoints is requesting data using an ID that does not exist.

Example request:

GET /users/999999

Expected behavior:

- API returns `404 Not Found` or equivalent error response
- response body explains resource absence
- status code matches API design

Example assertion:

pm.test("Status code should be 400", () => {
    pm.response.to.have.status(400);
});

pm.test("Response contains error structure", () => {
    const json = pm.response.json();
    pm.expect(json).to.have.property("error");
    pm.expect(json.details || json.error).to.exist;
});

pm.test("Error message should not be empty", () => {
    const json = pm.response.json();
    const text = JSON.stringify(json).toLowerCase();

    if (text.includes("validasi gagal")) {
        pm.expect(json.details.length).to.be.at.least(1);
    }
});

